{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569602"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22274"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22274"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.1,0.05,0.58,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111364"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15239"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93494"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2793"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6487"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45225"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111364"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of recent blood test results. He reports a six-month history of stable health without joint pain, swelling, or red, hot joints, and he has never had kidney stones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of stage 3 chronic kidney disease with an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 45 mL/min/1.73m2, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications are metformin, perindopril, and amlodipine. He drinks two standard drinks of beer daily and does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 136/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. There is no joint tenderness, swelling, or tophi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal serum urate 0.58 mmol/L (0.15-0.40), glycated haemoglobin 53 mmol/mol (20-42), creatinine 140 micromol/L (60-110), and estimated glomerular filtration rate 45 mL/min/1.73m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence allopurinol","Commence febuxostat","Start colchicine prophylaxis","Provide lifestyle advice only","Commence probenecid"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic hyperuricaemia is common in people with chronic kidney disease. Although elevated serum urate correlates with adverse renal and cardiovascular outcomes, randomised trials have not consistently shown that urate-lowering therapy improves estimated glomerular filtration rate decline or reduces cardiovascular events in people without gout. Current guidance recommends reserving urate-lowering therapy for clear indications (gout, tophi, or uric acid nephrolithiasis). In primary care, attention should focus on modifiable risks such as blood pressure, glycaemic control, medicines review, and alcohol intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide lifestyle advice only\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because the person has elevated serum urate without gout, tophi, or uric acid stones. Appropriate next steps include counselling on alcohol moderation, weight management, diet quality, and review of medicines that may raise urate, while optimising kidney and cardiovascular risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence allopurinol\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate here because there is no clear indication for urate-lowering therapy in asymptomatic hyperuricaemia. Initiating a xanthine oxidase inhibitor exposes the person to potential adverse effects and monitoring without proven benefit for kidney or cardiovascular outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence febuxostat\u003C/strong\u003E is similarly not indicated in the absence of gout, tophi, or uric acid stones. In addition, febuxostat use requires careful cardiovascular risk consideration, and there is no evidence that starting it for asymptomatic hyperuricaemia improves outcomes relevant to this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart colchicine prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary because prophylaxis is used when initiating urate-lowering therapy to reduce the risk of gout flares. Without starting urate-lowering medication and without a history of gout, colchicine offers no benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence probenecid\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate because uricosuric therapy is not indicated for asymptomatic hyperuricaemia and is relatively ineffective and potentially harmful in chronic kidney disease due to reduced efficacy at lower estimated glomerular filtration rate and increased risk of uric acid nephrolithiasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Do not start uric acid lowering therapy for asymptomatic hyperuricaemia, including in chronic kidney disease, unless there is a clear indication such as gout, tophi or uric acid stones.","Lowering serum urate has not been shown to slow chronic kidney disease progression or reduce cardiovascular events in the absence of symptomatic gout."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf","Kielstein JT, Pontremoli R, Burnier M. Management of Hyperuricemia in Patients with Chronic Kidney Disease: a Focus on Renal Protection. Curr Hypertens Rep. 2020 Oct 31;22(12):102. doi: 10.1007/s11906-020-01116-3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93494"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22274"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93494"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T12:54:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T12:58:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15239"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111364"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}